fine.\n\nBut what if `UIToast.destroy()` is called from outside `ToastManager`? 
For example, if someone creates a `UIToast` directly and later destroys it. The 
`ToastManager` wouldn\'t know. But that\'s expected - direct usage bypasses the 
manager.\n\nOK, so the ToastManager logic seems mostly correct after all. Let me
reconsider.\n\nWait, there IS an issue with `repositionToasts()`: when it calls 
`killTweensOf(this.scene, toast)` on the remaining toasts, it might kill their `
show()` animation if they were just created. But `show()` animation is quick (30
0ms), and `repositionToasts()` is called when a toast is dismissed. By the time 
a toast is dismissed, the other toasts have likely finished their show animation
. And even if not, killing the show tween and starting a reposition tween is pro
bably fine.\n\nActually, I realized I should also check the `UIAlert.show()` ani
mation duration. In `UIAlert.ts`:\n```typescript\nshow(): void {\n  killTweensOf
(this.scene, this);\n  this.scene.tweens.add({\n    targets: this,\n    alpha: 1
,\n    y: this.y - 20,\n    duration: UITweens.popup.duration,  // 200ms\n    ea
se: UITweens.popup.ease,          // Back.out\n  });\n```\n\nBut the design-spec
says for UIAlert:\n"show(): y: +20 → 0, alpha: 0 → 1, duration=200ms, ease=\'Bac
k.out\'"\n\nWait, `UITweens.popup.duration` is 200ms and `ease` is \'Back.out\'.
That matches! I was confusing it with UIToast show duration which is 300ms.\n\nB
ut wait, `UIAlert.hide()`:\n```typescript\nhide(): void {\n  killTweensOf(this.s
cene, this);\n  this.scene.tweens.add({\n    targets: this,\n    alpha: 0,\n    
y: this.y - 10,\n    duration: UITweens.fade.duration,  // 150ms\n    ease: UITw
eens.fade.ease,          // Power2\n  });\n```\n\nDesign-spec says hide should b
e 200ms, but code uses 150ms. This is a discrepancy.\n\nHowever, `docs/design-do
cs/ui-style-guide/03-component.md` says for UIAlert:\n"退场：`alpha 1 → 0`，`y -
10`，`duration=150ms`，`ease=\'Power2\'`"\n\nSo the ui-style-guide and code agre
e on 150ms, but the PRD-004 and design-spec say 200ms. Since the PRD-004 is the 
higher-level document and this PR is supposed to align with it, and the design-s
pec was specifically created for this issue, I think 200ms is the intended value
and the code has a minor bug. But it\'s arguable whether this is Major or Minor.
Given that the ui-style-guide (which was also updated in this PR) says 150ms, th
is might be a doc inconsistency rather than a code bug. I\'ll note it as a Minor
issue or doc inconsistency.\n\nActually wait - the design-spec.md is part of `de
signs/issue-19/` which is the design artifact for this PR. The PRD-004 is the pa
rent PRD. If both say 200ms, then the code should be 200ms. But the ui-style-gui
de was also updated in this PR and says 150ms. This is an internal inconsistency
in the project\'s documentation. Since my job is code review, I\'ll flag the inc
onsistency.\n\nLet me now check for any other issues. Let me look at the `SceneS
witchBar.ts` change.\n\nIn the diff:\n```typescript\nimport { UISegmentedControl
} from \'../../ui/UISegmentedControl\';\nimport { UITheme } from \'../../ui/util
s\';\n```\n\nPreviously it might have used direct Rectangle + emoji or something
. This change uses the proper UI component. That\'s good.\n\nWait, but `SceneSwi
tchBar` doesn\'t have any tests. The PR changes it but there\'s no test for it. 
Is that within scope? This PR is about UI component library redesign. SceneSwitc
hBar is a business component that uses UISegmentedControl. It doesn\'t necessari
ly need new tests in this PR.\n\nLet me check one more thing: `UIBadge` uses `UI
Theme.badgeSuccess` etc. which are defined in utils.ts. But `UIBadgeType` doesn\
't include `\'primary\'`? Wait, looking at the type:\n```typescript\nexport type
UIBadgeType = \'default\' | \'primary\' | \'success\' | \'warning\' | \'danger\'
| \'rare\' | \'epic\' | \'legendary\';\n```\n\nAnd the switch:\n```typescript\nc
ase \'primary\': return { bg: UITheme.stoneCyan, stroke: UITheme.stoneCyan };\n`
``\n\nOK, that\'s fine.\n\nLet me also check `UIButton.ts` for `pressedColor`:\n
```typescript\npressedColor: config.pressedColor ?? -1,\n```\n\nAnd in `pointerd
own`:\n```typescript\nif (this.background instanceof Phaser.GameObjects.Rectangl
e && this.config.pressedColor !== -1) {\n  this.background.setFillStyle(this.con
fig.pressedColor, 1);\n}\n```\n\nIf `pressedColor` is not provided, it defaults 
to -1 and the pressed color change is skipped. That\'s acceptable - the button j
ust doesn\'t change color on press, but it still has the scale animation.\n\nWai
t, looking at PRD-004 5.3:\n"增加 `pressedColor` 支持 Pressed 态独立颜色"\n\nIt 
doesn\'t say pressedColor is required. So defaulting to no color change is OK.\n
\nBut wait, there\'s a bug in UIButton: when `isDisabled=true` is passed in cons
tructor:\n```typescript\nif (this.config.isDisabled) {\n  target.disableInteract
ive();\n  this.setAlpha(0.6);\n  return;\n}\n```\n\nIt disables interactive and 
sets alpha, but does NOT set `useHandCursor: false` because `setInteractive({ us
eHandCursor: !this.config.isDisabled })` is called BEFORE the disabled check. Ac
tually, `target.setInteractive({ useHandCursor: !this.config.isDisabled });` is 
called, and since `isDisabled=true`, `useHandCursor` is `false`. Then `target.di
sableInteractive()` is called. So the hand cursor is never shown, which is corre
ct.\n\nBut what if `setDisabled(false)` is called later?\n```typescript\nsetDisa
bled(isDisabled: boolean): void {\n  this.config.isDisabled = isDisabled;\n  con
st target = this.background as Phaser.GameObjects.Rectangle & Phaser.GameObjects
.Image;\n\n  if (isDisabled) {\n    target.disableInteractive();\n    this.setAl
pha(0.6);\n  } else {\n    target.setInteractive({ useHandCursor: true });\n    
this.setAlpha(1);\n  }\n}\n```\n\nThis re-enables interactive with hand cursor. 
Good.\n\nHowever, when `setDisabled(false)` is called, the event listeners (`poi
nterover`, `pointerout`, `pointerdown`, `pointerup`) were already set up in the 
constructor. But wait - in the constructor, if `isDisabled=true`, the function r
eturns early before setting up those listeners:\n```typescript\nif (this.config.
isDisabled) {\n  target.disableInteractive();\n  this.setAlpha(0.6);\n  return;\
n}\n```\n\nSo when `setDisabled(false)` is called later, the event listeners wer
e NEVER set up! The button won\'t respond to hover/click after being re-enabled.
\n\nThis is a **Major** bug! The `setDisabled(false)` doesn\'t work if the butto
n was created with `isDisabled=true`.\n\nSimilarly, looking at `UISegmentedContr
ol.setOptionDisabled()`:\n```typescript\nsetOptionDisabled(index: number, isDisa
bled: boolean): void {\n  const option = this.config.options[index];\n  if (!opt
ion) return;\n  this.optionStates.set(option.key, isDisabled);\n  const containe
r = this.optionContainers.get(option.key);\n  if (container) {\n    const label 
= (container as unknown as { labelText?: Phaser.GameObjects.Text }).labelText;\n
   if (label) {\n      label.setAlpha(isDisabled ? 0.4 : 1);\n    }\n  }\n}\n```
\n\nThis only changes label alpha. It doesn\'t remove/add interactivity on the h
itArea. But the hitArea\'s `pointerdown` handler already checks:\n```typescript\
nhitArea.on(\'pointerdown\', () => {\n  if (this.optionStates.get(option.key)) r
eturn;\n  this.selectOption(option.key);\n});\n```\n\nSo disabled options are ha
ndled at the event handler level, not by removing interactivity. That\'s accepta
ble, though not as clean as removing interactivity entirely.\n\nNow let me check
`UIAvatar.ts` to see if it was updated properly in this PR.',
    encrypted=None
)
